<detall><id label=""><![CDATA[21246]]></id><title label="Titol"><![CDATA[Sweet St Medir is back!]]></title><excerpt label="Resum"><![CDATA[<strong>Festivals.</strong> Gràcia's and Sarrià-Sant Gervasi's sweet-throwers will be parading once again to pay tribute to the saint, handing out kilos of sweets for everyone!]]></excerpt><content label="Contingut"><![CDATA[<p>Tradition has it that St Medir was a peasant who died with his throat slit by the Romans back in the 4th century, having helped a bishop. Centuries later, the neighbourhoods of Gràcia, Sarrià, Sant Gervasi, and La Bordeta are paying homage to the saint with parades of groups giving out kilos and kilos of sweets. St Medir is back this Sunday, to fill the streets with colour and sweets!<br />
There will be a passacaglia in Gràcia in the morning and a parade of groups handing out sweets in the evening. There will also be a passacaglia in Sarrià-Sant Gervasi in the morning and on Sunday, 9 March, the groups handing out sweets will be concentrating at the Sant Medir Parish Church. Gràcia will also be playing host on Sunday to its diada castellera, an annually held day of &#8220;human-tower&#8221; building competitions.</p>
